
Men's Bible Study Guide

A Journey in Grace – Richard Belcher

Chapters 5 – 7

A Reformed Baptist Study for Men Walking in Truth and Grace

⸻

Chapter 5 – Total Depravity: The Depth of Our Need

Summary:
Belcher's story turns inward here — toward man's inability and God's sufficiency. In the Reformed Baptist view, total depravity doesn't mean man has lost the image of God, but that sin has corrupted every faculty: mind, heart, and will. We are not merely wounded; we are spiritually dead and dependent on sovereign mercy.

As Spurgeon put it:

"You must first feel that you are sick before you will consent to take the medicine. You must be condemned before you will seek pardon."
— C.H. Spurgeon, "The Sinner's End"

This doctrine humbles the proud but also frees us — because when we see how lost we were, we begin to grasp how mighty grace truly is.

Key Scriptures:
	•	Ephesians 2:1–5 – "You were dead in trespasses and sins… but God, being rich in mercy, made us alive."
	•	Romans 3:10–12 – "None is righteous, no, not one."
	•	John 6:44 – "No one can come to Me unless the Father who sent Me draws him."
	•	Jeremiah 17:9 – "The heart is deceitful above all things, and desperately sick."

⸻

Reflection Questions
	1.	When have you come face-to-face with the truth that you cannot fix yourself?
	2.	What parts of your life still try to operate on "self-reliance" instead of "grace dependence"?
	3.	Why is the doctrine of depravity especially difficult for men to admit or embrace?
	4.	How does total depravity magnify the glory of Christ's redeeming work?
	5.	How does understanding the depth of sin shape your prayer life and your patience toward others?

⸻

Group Discussion
	•	Discuss: Why does every generation of men try to downplay sin? What's the danger of softening this doctrine?
	•	How can we hold each other accountable to humility — not self-pity, but honest dependence on Christ?
	•	Spurgeon said, "A man cannot know the greatness of the mercy he enjoys until he knows the greatness of the mischief from which he has been delivered." What does that mean to you personally?
	•	In what ways can we teach our families to see the seriousness of sin and the beauty of grace at the same time?

⸻

Prayer Focus

"Lord, I confess my need for You in every breath. Tear down the illusion of strength that keeps me from seeking Your mercy. Let me boast only in the cross, where my helplessness met Your power."

