Chapter 6 – Unconditional Election: Chosen by Grace

Summary:
Belcher's protagonist wrestles here with God's sovereignty — the truth that salvation is rooted in God's choice, not man's decision. Unconditional election is not cold fatalism; it's warm assurance. God's electing love flows from His heart, not our merit.

R.C. Sproul wrote:

"The most terrifying thought a sinner can have is that God is just. The most comforting thought a saint can have is that God is gracious — and His grace was set on us before the foundation of the world."

The Reformed Baptist emphasis: Election does not undermine evangelism; it undergirds it. Because God has His people, we proclaim the gospel boldly, knowing His word will not return void.

Key Scriptures:
	•	Ephesians 1:3–6 – "He chose us in Him before the foundation of the world."
	•	Romans 9:16 – "It depends not on human will or exertion, but on God, who has mercy."
	•	2 Timothy 1:9 – "He saved us and called us… because of His own purpose and grace."
	•	John 15:16 – "You did not choose Me, but I chose you."

⸻

Reflection Questions
	1.	How do you respond to the idea that God's choice came before your choice?
	2.	Does election make you feel humbled or confused — and why?
	3.	How does unconditional election produce security rather than pride?
	4.	What difference does it make in your worship to know that God set His love on you eternally?
	5.	How does this truth motivate you to share the gospel more, not less?
	6.	What might your life look like if you truly rested in God's sovereign purpose day by day?

⸻

Group Discussion
	•	Men often equate control with leadership. How does God's sovereignty redefine true leadership?
	•	Read Romans 9:19–21 together. How do we submit to truths that make us uncomfortable without softening them?
	•	John Bunyan said:
"I was never out of His mind for one moment. He thought on me before the world was made."
What effect does that reality have on your confidence and peace?
	•	In practical terms, how does election lead to greater humility, courage, and prayerfulness in your home and workplace?

⸻

Prayer Focus

"Father, I praise You for choosing me before I could ever choose You. Let that truth crush my pride and lift my heart. Use me as an instrument to call others into Your sovereign grace."

